# Rust Macros

Macros are powerful but sharp. Prefer functions, traits, and generics; reach for macros only when they are the only way to eliminate real repetition.

## When to use macros

| Situation | Approach |
|---|---|
| Repetitive boilerplate with variable arity | `macro_rules!` |
| Custom `#[derive]` for a trait | Proc-macro (derive) |
| Domain-specific syntax or DSL | Proc-macro (function-like) |
| Adding behaviour to items by annotation | Proc-macro (attribute) |
| Anything achievable with generics or traits | Use generics/traits instead |

## `macro_rules!` hygiene

- Always use `$crate::` to refer to items from the defining crate inside a macro body — never bare paths:
  ```rust
  // BAD — breaks if the user has not imported the crate
  macro_rules! my_macro {
      () => { MyStruct::new() };
  }
  // GOOD
  macro_rules! my_macro {
      () => { $crate::MyStruct::new() };
  }
  ```
- Use `tt` (token tree) fragments for maximum flexibility; use typed fragments (`expr`, `ty`, `ident`, `path`, `block`, `stmt`) to get better error messages when input is wrong
- Wrap macro bodies in `{ }` or `( )` to avoid precedence surprises at the call site
- Never emit `use` statements from inside a macro — they pollute the caller's namespace
- Export macros intended for external use with `#[macro_export]`; keep internal helpers unexported

## Declarative macro patterns

```rust
// Correct repetition pattern
macro_rules! impl_from_str {
    ($($t:ty),+) => {
        $(
            impl FromStr for $t {
                type Err = ParseError;
                fn from_str(s: &str) -> Result<Self, Self::Err> {
                    s.parse().map(Self).map_err(Into::into)
                }
            }
        )+
    };
}

impl_from_str!(Foo, Bar, Baz);
```

- Test macros with `macro_rules! ... #[cfg(test)]` expansion tests and `trybuild` for compile-error cases
- Use `assert_matches!` (std) or the `matches!` macro rather than rolling your own pattern-matching assertion

## Procedural macros

Proc-macros live in a dedicated `*-derive` or `*-macros` crate — they cannot be in the same crate they affect.

- Use `syn` for parsing Rust token streams; use `quote` for generating code — do not hand-roll token manipulation
- Return a `proc_macro2::TokenStream` from your implementation function, then wrap it in `proc_macro::TokenStream` in the entry point:
  ```rust
  #[proc_macro_derive(MyTrait, attributes(my_attr))]
  pub fn my_derive(input: proc_macro::TokenStream) -> proc_macro::TokenStream {
      let input = syn::parse_macro_input!(input as syn::DeriveInput);
      impl_my_trait(input)
          .unwrap_or_else(syn::Error::into_compile_error)
          .into()
  }
  ```
- Use `syn::Error::new_spanned(...).into_compile_error()` to emit errors — never `panic!` inside a proc-macro, as it produces a terrible user experience
- Use `darling` to parse macro helper attributes declaratively instead of manual `syn` attribute parsing

## `#[derive(...)]` ordering convention

Consistently order derives: **Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, PartialOrd, Ord, Hash, Default**, then external crates (`Serialize`, `Deserialize`, `Error`, etc.):

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq, Eq, Hash, serde::Serialize, serde::Deserialize)]
pub struct Foo { ... }
```

## Trait coherence & orphan rules

- The orphan rule: you can only implement a trait for a type if you own **either** the trait **or** the type
- Use the newtype pattern to implement foreign traits on foreign types:
  ```rust
  // Cannot: impl Display for Vec<MyType> — Vec and Display are both foreign
  struct MyVec(Vec<MyType>);
  impl Display for MyVec { ... } // OK — you own MyVec
  ```
- Use sealed traits (see `rust-modules.mdc`) to prevent downstream `impl` of your trait on arbitrary types
- Blanket implementations (`impl<T: Foo> Bar for T`) affect ALL types — add them with care; they are a semver-breaking change to remove

## Testing macros

- Use `trybuild` to assert that macros produce specific compile errors:
  ```rust
  #[test]
  fn derive_missing_field_errors() {
      let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();
      t.compile_fail("tests/ui/missing_field.rs");
  }
  ```
- Use `macro_rules!` expansion tests with `assert_eq!(format!("{:?}", result), expected)` for output validation
